id="post-1735" class="hentry p1 post publish author-drew category-bread tag-recipe-card comments-open pings-open y2008 m12 d11 h03 slug-how-to-make-crusty-italian-bread"><h1 class="entry-title">How To Make Crusty Italian Bread</h1><div
class="entry-meta"><span
class="meta-prep meta-prep-author">By </span><span
class="author vcard"><a
class="url fn n" href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/author/drook/" title="View all posts by Drew">Drew</a></span><span
class="meta-sep meta-sep-entry-date"> | </span><span
class="meta-prep meta-prep-entry-date">Published: </span><span
class="entry-date"><abbr
class="published" title="2008-12-11T02:19:00-0500">December 11, 2008</abbr></span></div><div
class="entry-content"><p><img
class="hero-pic" src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-165245_Med.jpg" alt="" /></p><p>The right bread can be the difference between a cheesesteak and a &#8220;genuine Philly style steak and cheese sandwich.&#8221;</p><p>Philadelphians understand that line. The rest of you might be scratching your heads wondering what I&#8217;m talking about. In a word: <a
href="http://amorosobaking.com/" target="_NEW">Amoroso&#8217;s</a>. Okay, that&#8217;s not helping you yet, is it?</p><p>Okay, put it this way. When you&#8217;re in Italy, you wouldn&#8217;t describe a restaurant as &#8220;Italian&#8221;. Kind of obvious, right? Well, when you&#8217;re in Philly you wouldn&#8217;t ask for a &#8220;Philly style steak sandwich&#8221;. You&#8217;d ask for a cheesesteak. Unless you want people to look at you like you just stepped in a pile of dog poo.</p><p>And if you&#8217;re somewhere else? &#8220;Philly style&#8221; on the sign is a dead giveaway that it&#8217;s <em>not</em>. It&#8217;s either a cheesesteak or it&#8217;s not, no qualifiers needed.</p><p>All of which is a <em>really</em> long way of getting to the point: I miss Amoroso&#8217;s <em>so bad</em>. Since I can&#8217;t get it here, I&#8217;m going to make my own. I may not get it perfect on the first try, but I&#8217;ll keep tweaking it until it&#8217;s as close as I can get.<br
/> <span
id="more-1735"></span></p><h3>Ingredients</h3><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-124229_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-124229_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" align="right" /></a><br
/> 1 package (1/4 ounce, 2-1/2 teaspoons) active dry yeast<br
/> 1-1/4 cups warm water (105°-115°)<br
/> 3 cups unbleached flour or all-purpose flour<br
/> 2 teaspoons sugar<br
/> 1 teaspoon salt<br
/> 1 tablespoon olive oil<br
/> cornmeal for dusting</p><h3>Directions</h3><p>Dissolve the yeast in a quarter-cup of warm water. You should actually check the temperature of the water. Too cold and it won&#8217;t activate, too hot and you can kill the yeast.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-124827_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-124827_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a> <a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-124905_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-124905_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a><br
/> <a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-124947_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-124947_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>Give the yeast a few minutes, until it starts bubbling, then mix it in with the rest of the warm water.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-125134_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-125134_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a> <a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-125148_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-125148_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>Add the flour, sugar and salt and stir.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-125300_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-125300_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a> <a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-125426_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-125426_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a><br
/> <a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-125446_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-125446_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a> <a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-125524_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-125524_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>Don&#8217;t add the oil until after you&#8217;ve worked the water and flour together. Otherwise the oil will coat the proteins and prevent gluten formation. Gluten lets the dough stretch when it rises, making it light and chewy instead of crumbling like cake.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-125626_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-125626_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>After mixing the oil in, turn the dough out onto a clean, floured surface to knead.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-130402_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-130402_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>Stretch the dough away from you, fold it back, turn a quarter turn and repeat. Once the dough is well incorporated, slap it on the surface a few times. This will encourage more gluten production leading to a lighter, airier bread.</p><p><object
classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000" width="425" height="344" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0"><param
name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><param
name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /><param
name="src" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/70sPrSwRCG4&amp;hl=en&amp;fs=1" /><param
name="allowfullscreen" value="true" /><embed
type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="425" height="344" src="http://www.youtube.com/v/70sPrSwRCG4&amp;hl=en&amp;fs=1" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true"></embed></object></p><p>When the dough is smooth and silky, continue kneading for another several minutes. You can work it with both hands and keep turning the dough, or just hit it from opposite angles with each hand.</p><p><object
classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000" width="425" height="344" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0"><param
name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><param
name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /><param
name="src" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/G2a0RxfB_9Y&amp;hl=en&amp;fs=1" /><param
name="allowfullscreen" value="true" /><embed
type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="425" height="344" src="http://www.youtube.com/v/G2a0RxfB_9Y&amp;hl=en&amp;fs=1" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true"></embed></object></p><p>Once the dough is thoroughly kneaded, place it in an oiled <a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/blog/2008/09/great-great-grandma-winnifreds-non/" target="_NEW">bowl</a>. Toss the dough around so it is coated with oil all the way around.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-131138_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-131138_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a> <a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-131227_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-131227_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>Cover the dough with plastic wrap, pressed right up against the dough. This will prevent a skin from forming on the dough, allowing it to rise more.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-131259_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-131259_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>Put the bowl someplace warm until the dough has doubled in size, about 1-1/2 to 2 hours.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-141919_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-141919_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>Pre-heat the oven to 425°. If you have a pizza stone, put it on the bottom rack. Otherwise, place a baking sheet upside-down on the bottom rack.</p><p>Turn the dough out onto a floured surface and punch down to knock out most of the air out. Don&#8217;t go crazy and try to turn it into a pancake. Just give it a quick couple of hits.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-142029_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-142029_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>Roll the dough out into a loaf shape and cut it in half. You can form the halves into loaves or, like I did here, divide each half into three smaller pieces.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-142116_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-142116_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a> <a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-142141_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-142141_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>Roll out the pieces of dough until they are about 6-9 inches long.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-142304_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-142304_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>If you have a peel (the large wooden spatula you see in pizza shops) use that. If not, a wooden cutting board will work. Dust it with cornmeal so the dough doesn&#8217;t stick.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-142510_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-142510_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a> <a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-142524_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-142524_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>Cover the loaves with plastic and allow to rise for another 40 minutes. They should roughly double in width.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-144400_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-144400_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a> <a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-161718_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-161718_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>Cut each loaf down the middle with the <em>sharpest blade you have</em>. If you don&#8217;t have anything that is absolutely razor sharp, use a razor blade. You want to cut about a quarter-inch deep in a single quick stroke without sawing back-and-forth. This will prevent the bread from bursting open when it rises in the oven.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-161837_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-161837_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>Transfer the loaves onto the baking stone. Leave room between loaves for them to rise some more.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-161955_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-161955_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>If they don&#8217;t all fit on your stone, put the rest on an upside-down baking sheet.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-162238_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-162238_Sm.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /></a></p><p>Bake at 425° for 10 minutes, then turn the oven down to 400° and bake another 25-30 minutes. To check if they&#8217;re done, pick one loaf up and thump on the bottom with your thumb. If it has a hollow sound, it&#8217;s done.</p><p>If you want really crusty bread, great for dipping in olive oil or marinara sauce, place a pan of water in the bottom of the oven. The steam will keep a skin from forming too fast, giving the bread more time to rise. It will also make the crust crisper.</p><p>Don&#8217;t put the loaves near the top. The radiant heat from the top of the stove will brown the crust too much, too fast. Guess which ones in the picture below were on the baking sheet?</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-165120_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-165120_Med.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="375" /></a></p><p>Serve immediately with butter, or with olive oil and balsamic vinegar for dipping.</p><p><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-165245_Lg.jpg" target="_NEW" rel="lightbox[1735]"><img
src="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/albums/italian-bread/081206-165245_Med.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="375" /></a></p><p>And that&#8217;s it.</p><p>Or &#8230; let them cool off and maybe use them for sandwiches. Maybe I&#8217;ll have something special comingng up next. You think? Maybe?</p><div
style="text-align:center;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:2em;"><a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/recipe-card/?ID=1735">Recipe card</a></div> <br
/> <em><strong>Want more like this?</strong> For more recipes like this, that you can hold right in your hands, and write on, take notes, tear pages out if you want (Gosh, you're tough on books, aren't you?) you might be interested in <a
href="http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com/the-book/">How To Cook Like Your Grandmother, 2nd edition, Illustrated</a>. Or to learn your way around the kitchen, check out <a
href="http://www.startingfromscratchbook.com/">Starting From Scratch: The Owner's Manual for Your Kitchen</a>.</em><br
/><br
