id="comment-24548" class="comment c19 byuser comment-author-drook bypostauthor c-y2009 c-m06 c-d05 c-h23 depth-1"><div
class="comment-author vcard"><img
alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a18d426338d4b707ab1d2f4e037af39?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=PG' class='photo avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> <span
class="fn n"><a
href='http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url url'>Drew</a></span></div><div
class="comment-meta">Posted June 5, 2009 at 11:06 pm <span
class="meta-sep">|</span> <a
href="#comment-24548" title="Permalink to this comment">Permalink</a></div><div
class="comment-content"><p>The pan of water in the bottom is how you get the crustiness. For the chewiness, substitute bread flour (high gluten flour) for at least half the white flour. If you&#39;re feeling extravagant, use <em>all</em> bread flour.</p><p>For handling, you want to knead it to &quot;windowpane&quot; consistency. That means if you pull off a little piece of dough, you can stretch it thin enough to almost see through without it breaking.</p></div><div
class="comment-reply-link"><a
rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2008/12/how-to-make-crusty-italian-bread/?replytocom=24548#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-24548", "24548", "respond", "1735")'>Reply</a></div></li><li
