id="comment-27046" class="comment c36 byuser comment-author-drook bypostauthor c-y2010 c-m01 c-d31 c-h18 alt depth-1"><div
class="comment-author vcard"><img
alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a18d426338d4b707ab1d2f4e037af39?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=PG' class='photo avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> <span
class="fn n"><a
href='http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url url'>Drew</a></span></div><div
class="comment-meta">Posted January 31, 2010 at 5:57 pm <span
class="meta-sep">|</span> <a
href="#comment-27046" title="Permalink to this comment">Permalink</a></div><div
class="comment-content"><p>Steve, bread flour will help with the rise. As for kneading, it could be either too much <em>or</em> too little. You have to knead it enough to develop the gluten (stretch out the protein chains in the flour once they&#8217;ve been hydrated) but if you overdo it the bread can get tough.</p><p>One other thing to try is letting the second rise go longer. I have this bad habit of wanting the bread <em>right now</em> and don&#8217;t give it as long as I really should. You want the most rise you can get without getting flimsy and falling over on itself. It just takes practice to recognize what it should look like at each stage.</p></div><div
class="comment-reply-link"><a
rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2008/12/how-to-make-crusty-italian-bread/?replytocom=27046#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-27046", "27046", "respond", "1735")'>Reply</a></div></li><li
