id="comment-27333" class="comment c38 byuser comment-author-drook bypostauthor c-y2010 c-m02 c-d23 c-h15 alt depth-1"><div
class="comment-author vcard"><img
alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a18d426338d4b707ab1d2f4e037af39?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=PG' class='photo avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> <span
class="fn n"><a
href='http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url url'>Drew</a></span></div><div
class="comment-meta">Posted February 23, 2010 at 2:16 pm <span
class="meta-sep">|</span> <a
href="#comment-27333" title="Permalink to this comment">Permalink</a></div><div
class="comment-content"><p>Lee Ann, I&#8217;ve had far too many disappointments with deflating bread. The baking stone gives a slightly better crust, but I still have trouble moving the dough onto it without deflating. And don&#8217;t even get me started on slashing the top.</p><p>If yours went down just from pulling off the plastic, then yes, you let it rise a bit too much. A smaller rise that makes it into the oven intact beats a nice big rise that goes *poof* when you touch it. (You could also try a bit more oil on the plastic before you cover the dough.)</p><p>And by the way, your first time with bread flour you&#8217;re going to tell yourself, &#8220;Oh, so <em>that&#8217;s</em> how this is supposed to work.&#8221;</p></div><div
class="comment-reply-link"><a
rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2008/12/how-to-make-crusty-italian-bread/?replytocom=27333#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-27333", "27333", "respond", "1735")'>Reply</a></div></li><li
