id="comment-30696" class="comment c81 byuser comment-author-drook bypostauthor c-y2010 c-m11 c-d10 c-h15 depth-1"><div
class="comment-author vcard"><img
alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a18d426338d4b707ab1d2f4e037af39?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=PG' class='photo avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> <span
class="fn n"><a
href='http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url url'>Drew</a></span></div><div
class="comment-meta">Posted November 10, 2010 at 2:03 pm <span
class="meta-sep">|</span> <a
href="#comment-30696" title="Permalink to this comment">Permalink</a></div><div
class="comment-content"><p>William, I always lose volume transferring to the hot stone. I&#8217;m starting to think I&#8217;d be better off keeping the stone for pizza and just leaving the bread on the pan it rose on.</p><p>For the crust, it&#8217;s all about having a steamy environment. I mentioned you can put a pan of water in the bottom for that. There are a few other methods that might work better, though. First, put a heavy-bottomed skillet (like cast iron) in the oven while it&#8217;s preheating. When you put the bread in, add a few ice cubes to the skillet.</p><p>Another method, common in bakeries, is to use a spray bottle of water. Spray the inside of the oven when you but the bread in.</p><p>A combination of methods might be best. For my next batch I&#8217;m going to use the skillet and ice cubes <em>and</em> spray with the spray bottle. I&#8217;ll keep you posted.</p><p>As for Sarcone&#8217;s, I recognize the name, but can&#8217;t say whether I&#8217;ve ever had them.</p></div><div
class="comment-reply-link"><a
rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2008/12/how-to-make-crusty-italian-bread/?replytocom=30696#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-30696", "30696", "respond", "1735")'>Reply</a></div></li><li
