class="comment-content"><p>I made just two loaves as well, and the cooking time was fine for me, the bread came out beautifully.</p></div><div
class="comment-reply-link"><a
rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2008/12/how-to-make-crusty-italian-bread/?replytocom=31941#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-31941", "31941", "respond", "1735")'>Reply</a></div></li></ul></li><li
id="comment-31940" class="comment c106 byuser comment-author-drook bypostauthor c-y2011 c-m03 c-d12 c-h12 alt depth-1"><div
class="comment-author vcard"><img
alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a18d426338d4b707ab1d2f4e037af39?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=PG' class='photo avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> <span
class="fn n"><a
href='http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url url'>Drew</a></span></div><div
class="comment-meta">Posted March 12, 2011 at 11:15 am <span
class="meta-sep">|</span> <a
href="#comment-31940" title="Permalink to this comment">Permalink</a></div><div
class="comment-content"><p>Cooking time is all about how far it is to the center of the thickest part. If you do round loaves, the cooking time will be a bit longer. If you do them in bread pans it will be even longer than that. How much longer? I don&#8217;t really know, since I always use this for either steak sandwiches or garlic bread.</p></div><div
class="comment-reply-link"><a
rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2008/12/how-to-make-crusty-italian-bread/?replytocom=31940#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-31940", "31940", "respond", "1735")'>Reply</a></div></li><li
id="comment-31981" class="comment c107 c-y2011 c-m03 c-d22 c-h22 depth-1"><div
class="comment-author vcard"><img
alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9de1e544d45a9e28078c951d13c64bed?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=PG' class='photo avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> <span
class="fn n">Travis</span></div><div
class="comment-meta">Posted March 22, 2011 at 10:07 pm <span
class="meta-sep">|</span> <a
href="#comment-31981" title="Permalink to this comment">Permalink</a></div><div
class="comment-content"><p>After the dough is kneaded, and placed in a bowl with Olive Oil, is it OK to let the dough sit over night, or could i refrigerate it after the two hours? I don&#8217;t want to lessen the quality of dough by letting it sit over night if that is the result.</p><p>Thanks!</p></div><div
class="comment-reply-link"><a
rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2008/12/how-to-make-crusty-italian-bread/?replytocom=31981#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-31981", "31981", "respond", "1735")'>Reply</a></div><ul
class='children'><li
id="comment-31982" class="comment c108 byuser comment-author-drook bypostauthor c-y2011 c-m03 c-d22 c-h23 alt depth-2"><div
class="comment-author vcard"><img
alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a18d426338d4b707ab1d2f4e037af39?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=PG' class='photo avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> <span
class="fn n"><a
href='http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url url'>Drew</a></span></div><div
class="comment-meta">Posted March 22, 2011 at 11:11 pm <span
class="meta-sep">|</span> <a
href="#comment-31982" title="Permalink to this comment">Permalink</a></div><div
class="comment-content"><p>Some people prefer to let the dough rise more slowly. The colder it is, the slower it will rise &#8212; you can freeze dough and the yeast will go completely dormant. When it warms up, it will start to rise again.</p><p>Usually you would refrigerate (or freeze) the dough before the second rise.</p></div><div
class="comment-reply-link"><a
rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2008/12/how-to-make-crusty-italian-bread/?replytocom=31982#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-31982", "31982", "respond", "1735")'>Reply</a></div></li></ul></li><li
id="comment-32041" class="comment c109 c-y2011 c-m04 c-d02 c-h15 depth-1"><div
class="comment-author vcard"><img
alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/798aed1a015d4fa9823bd91b97435bff?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=PG' class='photo avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> <span
class="fn n">Jana</span></div><div
class="comment-meta">Posted April 2, 2011 at 3:48 pm <span
class="meta-sep">|</span> <a
href="#comment-32041" title="Permalink to this comment">Permalink</a></div><div
class="comment-content"><p>I tried this recipe and now it&#8217;s all I use.  I do a few things a little different, first I let it rise on top of the stove while it&#8217;r heating up and for only about 1 hour.  Then I split the ball in two and form a braid on a lightly oiled cooking sheet.  I place a pyrex dish on the bottom rack filled halfway with water while it bakes.  I also brush on egg wash (one egg, yolk and white) before I bake it, I will attach a photo next time I make it, it tastes amazing and looks amazing too, very much a crowd pleaser!</p></div><div
class="comment-reply-link"><a
rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2008/12/how-to-make-crusty-italian-bread/?replytocom=32041#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-32041", "32041", "respond", "1735")'>Reply</a></div></li><li
