/> Flavor-wise the bread is turning out great but I can&#8217;t seem to master the crusty crust part &#8212; coming out soft. Instead of using a water bottle my Uncle says place an ice-cube in a small tray, tried it today &#8212; didn&#8217;t work. Any suggestions?</p></div><div
class="comment-reply-link"><a
rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2008/12/how-to-make-crusty-italian-bread/?replytocom=32053#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-32053", "32053", "respond", "1735")'>Reply</a></div></li><li
id="comment-32055" class="comment c112 byuser comment-author-drook bypostauthor c-y2011 c-m04 c-d05 c-h09 alt depth-1"><div
class="comment-author vcard"><img
alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a18d426338d4b707ab1d2f4e037af39?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=PG' class='photo avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> <span
class="fn n"><a
href='http://cooklikeyourgrandmother.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url url'>Drew</a></span></div><div
class="comment-meta">Posted April 5, 2011 at 9:47 am <span
class="meta-sep">|</span> <a
href="#comment-32055" title="Permalink to this comment">Permalink</a></div><div
class="comment-content"><p>Jeff, some bakeries keep a spray bottle handy and spray the inside of the oven with water before closing it. The trick is to get as much steam in there as possible.</p><p>Try a shallower, wider dish &#8212; maybe a pie plate &#8212; so you get more surface area with less volume. And make sure the water is hot before it goes in the oven.</p></div><div
class="comment-reply-link"><a
rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2008/12/how-to-make-crusty-italian-bread/?replytocom=32055#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-32055", "32055", "respond", "1735")'>Reply</a></div></li></ol><div
